  "prompt": "Why does hair turn grey as people age?",
  "response": "Hair turns grey as people age due to a combination of genetic, environmental, and biological factors that affect the production and maintenance of melanin, the pigment responsible for hair color. Here are the main reasons:\n\n1. **Melanocyte Decline**: Melanocytes are cells in hair follicles that produce melanin. As people age, melanocytes gradually decrease in number and activity, leading to less melanin being produced. This results in grey or white hair.\n\n2. **Genetic Factors**: Genetics play a significant role in determining when someone will start to go grey. The timing and pattern of greying can be inherited from one's parents.\n\n3. **Oxidative Stress**: Over time, oxidative stress caused by free radicals can damage cells, including melanocytes. This can accelerate the decline in melanin production.\n\n4. **Hormonal Changes**: Hormonal fluctuations associated with aging can also influence melanin production. For example, changes in levels of certain hormones might reduce the activity of melanocytes.\n\n5. **Environmental Factors**: Exposure to certain environmental factors, such as ultraviolet (UV) radiation or pollutants, can contribute to the greying process by increasing oxidative stress and damaging melanocytes.\n\nWhile these factors collectively contribute to the natural aging process and the eventual greying of hair, the specific age at which this occurs varies widely among individuals.",
